text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeArticle:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingComment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!What affects the accent of an adult language-learner%0a%0a:Author: rachelc%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aWhat factors affect the accent that an adult has once they speak a language fluently?%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn general, it seems that people who learn to speak another language fluently at a young will also speak with the accent of a native speaker, while people who learn to speak languages fluently as a teenager or adult will most likely have an accent for the rest of their lives. However, there are some exceptions to this rule, one of which that comes to mind is Nikkie de Jager from the YouTube channel NikkieTutorials. I had always thought that she was a native English speaker, but going back to her videos from when she was around 18 years old, I was surprised to find that she had a distinct Dutch accent, and in fact had lived in the Netherlands her entire life. My question is then, are there any common factors that help some adults achieve native or near-native pronunciation? Does the later into adulthood that you learn a language affect your accent? Does pronunciation naturally improve with time for all non-native speakers of a language? Do adults reach a limit past which they won't be able to improve their accent? As someone currently learning a new language I always wonder what steps I can take to effectively improve my accent while still managing my expectations for how accurate my pronunciation will become. %0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210206-231018-680180#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-06.02.2021 - 15:10-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210206-231018-680180 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!sarah_tandean%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a''''''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aI think that if someone has an accent when speaking a certain language, it's because that language contains consonant or vowel sounds that don't exist in their native language. So probably if you tried to replicate a sound by doing the necessary tongue position etc and practice it enough, you would be able to diminish your accent. Adding on to what Emma said, I think that it's easier for children to do this because in general, the older you get, the harder it is to learn new skills. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210206-231018-680180#%0a#foxbegin 210203-044149-750350#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-02.02.2021 - 20:41-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a!!!!!emma_p%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a''''''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aThis is really interesting! I'll share as an additional insight that I took Spanish all throughout high school, and I generally had my teachers notice that I had fairly good pronunciation. That was always because I was actively trying to imitate the sounds. I wonder if children do that more naturally because they're used to learning languages via imitating an adult. I also wonder if their speaking patterns just aren't as set in yet, which makes them easy to adjust. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210203-044149-750350#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:Section: :)%0a(:Category: PracticeCategory:)
